I101

Structures [7] and [8] have the substituents trans to one another, but in
[7] they are both equatorial while in [8] they are both axial. Structures [9]
and [lo] have the cis relationship between the groups, but the t-butyl and
chlorine are equatorial-axial in [9] and axial-equatorial in [lo]. t-Butyl groups
are very large and bulky and much more steric hindrance results when a
t-butyl group is in an axial position than when chlorine is in an axial position
(Figure 3.10). Hence the equilibrium between the two conformational forms
of the trans isomer strongly favors structure [7] over structure [8] because
both t-butyl and chlorine are equatorial. For the cis isomer, structure [9] is
favored over [lo] to accommodate the t-butyl group in the equatorial position.
When there are two substituents in the cis-1,4 arrangement on a cyclohexane ring, neither of which will go easily into an axial position, then it

