saturated compounds. These reactions have much in common in their mechanisms and have been much studied from this point of view. They are also of
considerable synthetic and analytical utility. The addition of water to alkenes
(hydration) is particularly important for the preparation of a number of commercially important alcohols. Thus ethyl alcohol and t-butyl alcohol are made
on a very large scale by hydrating the corresponding alkenes (ethene and 2methylpropene), using sulfuric or phosphoric acids as catalysts.

