to 71 bonding between carbon and the attached oxygen or halogen:

This is a matter of controversy. Such structures lead to an increase of n
bonding but with an associated separation of charge wherein electron-attracting nuclei such as oxygen and fluorine become positive, and weakly electronattracting atoms become negative. There may be some degree of stabilization
connected with resonance of this type but it is small at best. However, what is
more certain is that attack of a positive reagent such as Br@on CH,=CHOR will occur at the 2 carbon, not at the 1 carbon, because more 71 bonding is
