Isopropyl alcohol and t-butyl alcohol are also manufactured by hydration
of the corresponding alkenes. The industrial synthesis of methyl alcohol
involves hydrogenation of carbon monoxide. Although this reaction has a
favorable A H value of -28.4 kcal, it requires high pressures and high temperatures and a suitable catalyst; excellent conversions are achieved using a
zinc oxide-chromic oxide catalyst:

