attack by basic reagents, but removal of a hydrogen a to a carbonyl group
results in the formation of a considerably stabilized anion with a substa~ltial
proportion of the negative charge on oxygen. As a result, hydrogens a to
carbonyl groups have acidic character and can be removed as protons. Incontrast to the dissociation of many weak acids (e.g., CH3C0,H, H3B03, HF),
the acidic proton on carbon is removed slowly and equilibrium between the
ketone and its enolate anion [I] is not established rapidly. The reverse reaction is also slow and, as a result, the enolate anion has ample time to add a
proton to oxygen to form the en01 (this process is at least 10'' times faster
than conversion to the ketone).

