Ammonia and primary, secondary, and tertiary amines have the same base
strengths within perhaps a factor of 50, as can be seen from the data in
Table 16.2. There is no evidence for formation of undissociated amine hydroxides such as R3NHOH, any more than there is for NH,OH.
Unsaturated amines are often very weak bases. An example with C-N
unsaturation is pyridine, C5H5N,which is a nitrogen analog of benzene, often
called a heterocycle because not all of the atoms in the ring are of the same
element. Pyridine, K, = 1.7 x lo-', is less basic by a factor of about lo5 than
aliphatic amines.

