amines. For acetamide, KB is about
(the KBHaof the conjugate acid is
10) and acetamide is " half-protonated" in 1 M sulfuric acid.

-

The proton can become attached either to nitrogen or to oxygen. Nitrogen
is, of course, intrinsically more basic than oxygen, but formation of the
N-conjugate acid would cause loss of all the resonance stabilization energy of
the amide. Infrared and nmr studies of amide cations reveal that the 0protonated form predominates; the equilibrium between the two is established
so rapidly, however, that the N-protonated form appears to serve as an intermediate in some reactions.
