glycine in water to contain four species in rapid equilibrium.

conjugate acid
of glycine

conjugate base
of glycine

dipolar ion
(zwitterion)

The proportions of these species are expected to change with pH, the conjugate acid being the predominant form at low pH values and the conjugate
base being favored at high pH values. Since the establishment of equilibrium
between the uncharged molecule and the dipolar ion (often called a "zwitterion ") involves no net change in hydrogen or hydroxide ion concentrations,
the ratio of these two substances is independent of pH. The position of equilibrium, however, strongly favors the zwitterion.

A titration curve starting with glycine hydrochloride is shown in Figure
17-1. Two equivalents of base are required to convert 0NH3CH2C02Hto
NH2CH2COZe. The pH of half-neutralization during addition of the first
equivalent of base corresponds to proton loss from the carboxyl group of the
conjugate acid of glycine, K,,, = 5 x loe3, whereas the pH of half-neutralization during the addition of the second equivalent of base corresponds to
proton loss from the ammonium group of the zwitterion, KHA= 2 x 10-lo.
There will be a pH on the titration curve where the concentration of zwit0

terion is at a maximum and where the concentration of NH3CH2C0,H will
~@
these
. two ions conbe just equal to the concentration of N H ~ C H ~ C O If
duct electric current equally well, then, in an electrolytic experiment, there
8

Figure 17.1 Titration curve of the conjugate acid of glycine, NH,CH2C02H,
with base.

