The backbone of DNA is thus a polyphosphate ester of a 1,3-glycol.

With the details of the sugar residue included, the structure of DNA becomes as shown in Figure 17.9.
Each of the sugar residues of DNA is bonded at the 1 position to one of
four bases, adenine [7], guanine [a], cytosine [9], and thymine [lo], through
an N-glycosidic linkage. The four bases are derivatives of either 2-hydroxypyrimidine or purine, both of which are heterocyclic nitrogen bases.

