Organic compounds of phosphorus include phosphate esters, R-OPO(OH), , phosphonic acids, R-PO(OH), , and organophosphines, R3P.
Phosphate esters may exist as polyphosphates, an important example of
which is adenosine triphosphate, ATP.
Phosphines can form phosphonium-salts, R4PeX@, analogous to ammonium salts. When treated with phenyllithium, a methylphosphonium ion loses
a proton to give a methylenephosphorane.

