B. CYCLIZATION REACTIONS OF A L K Y N E S

Alkynes can act as dienophiles in the Diels-Alder reaction to produce nonconjugated cyclohexadienes.

Acetylene can be readily polymerized to cyclooctatetraene by the action of
nickel cyanide.

With this reaction, cyclooctatetraene could be manufactured easily on a
large scale; however, profitable commercial uses of the substance have yet
to be developed.
It is easy to become confused about the reactions of alkynes with transitionmetal ions. Acetylene, for example, is hydrated under the influence of Hg"
(Section 5.4); it forms salts with Ag' (Section 5.5); it is dimerized to vinylacetylene by Cul (Section 5.4); it is polymerized to cyclooctatetraene by Ni"
(above); and we shall see later in this chapter that it and other alkynes can be
oxidatively coupled by the action of Cu".
